# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: text-summarization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:text-summarization/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Text summarization is usually implemented by natural language processing methods, designed to locate the most informative sentences in a given document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] On the other hand, visual content can be summarized using computer vision algorithms.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Image summarization is the subject of ongoing research; existing approaches typically attempt to display the most representative images from a given image collection, or generate a video that only includes the most important content from the entire collection.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Video summarization algorithms identify and extract from the original video content the most important frames (*key-frames*), and/or the most important video segments (*key-shots*), normally in a temporally ordered fashion.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Video summaries simply retain a carefully selected subset of the original video frames and, therefore, are not identical to the output of video synopsis algorithms, where *new* video frames are being synthesized based on the original video content.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In 2022 Google Docs released an automatic summarization feature.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] There are two general approaches to automatic summarization: extraction and abstraction.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Here, content is extracted from the original data, but the extracted content is not modified in any way.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Examples of extracted content include key-phrases that can be used to "tag" or index a text document, or key sentences (including headings) that collectively comprise an abstract, and representative images or video segments, as stated above.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For text, extraction is analogous to the process of skimming, where the summary (if available), headings and subheadings, figures, the first and last paragraphs of a section, and optionally the first and last sentences in a paragraph are read before one chooses to read the entire document in detail.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Other examples of extraction that include key sequences of text in terms of clinical relevance (including patient/problem, intervention, and outcome).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Abstractive summarization methods generate new text that did not exist in the original text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Abstractive methods build an internal semantic representation of the original content (often called a language model), and then use this representation to create a summary that is closer to what a human might express.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Abstraction may transform the extracted content by paraphrasing sections of the source document, to condense a text more strongly than extraction.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Such transformation, however, is computationally much more challenging than extraction, involving both natural language processing and often a deep understanding of the domain of the original text in cases where the original document relates to a special field of knowledge.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] "Paraphrasing" is even more difficult to apply to images and videos, which is why most summarization systems are extractive.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Approaches aimed at higher summarization quality rely on combined software and human effort.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In Machine Aided Human Summarization, extractive techniques highlight candidate passages for inclusion (to which the human adds or removes text).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In Human Aided Machine Summarization, a human post-processes software output, in the same way that one edits the output of automatic translation by Google Translate.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] There are broadly two types of extractive summarization tasks depending on what the summarization program focuses on.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The first is *generic summarization*, which focuses on obtaining a generic summary or abstract of the collection (whether documents, or sets of images, or videos, news stories etc.).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The second is *query relevant summarization*, sometimes called *query-based summarization*, which summarizes objects specific to a query.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Summarization systems are able to create both query relevant text summaries and generic machine-generated summaries depending on what the user needs.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] An example of a summarization problem is document summarization, which attempts to automatically produce an abstract from a given document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Sometimes one might be interested in generating a summary from a single source document, while others can use multiple source documents (for example, a cluster of articles on the same topic).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This problem is called multi-document summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A related application is summarizing news articles.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Imagine a system, which automatically pulls together news articles on a given topic (from the web), and concisely represents the latest news as a summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Image collection summarization is another application example of automatic summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It consists in selecting a representative set of images from a larger set of images.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A summary in this context is useful to show the most representative images of results in an image collection exploration system.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Video summarization is a related domain, where the system automatically creates a trailer of a long video.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This also has applications in consumer or personal videos, where one might want to skip the boring or repetitive actions.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, in surveillance videos, one would want to extract important and suspicious activity, while ignoring all the boring and redundant frames captured.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] At a very high level, summarization algorithms try to find subsets of objects (like set of sentences, or a set of images), which cover information of the entire set.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] These algorithms model notions like diversity, coverage, information and representativeness of the summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Query based summarization techniques, additionally model for relevance of the summary with the query.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Some techniques and algorithms which naturally model summarization problems are TextRank and PageRank, Submodular set function, Determinantal point process, maximal marginal relevance (MMR) etc.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] You are given a piece of text, such as a journal article, and you must produce a list of keywords or key[phrase]s that capture the primary topics discussed in the text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In the case of research articles, many authors provide manually assigned keywords, but most text lacks pre-existing keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, news articles rarely have keyphrases attached, but it would be useful to be able to automatically do so for a number of applications discussed below.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A keyphrase extractor might select "Army Corps of Engineers", "President Bush", "New Orleans", and "defective flood-control pumps" as keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] These are pulled directly from the text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In contrast, an abstractive keyphrase system would somehow internalize the content and generate keyphrases that do not appear in the text, but more closely resemble what a human might produce, such as "political negligence" or "inadequate protection from floods".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Abstraction requires a deep understanding of the text, which makes it difficult for a computer system.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] They can enable document browsing by providing a short summary, improve information retrieval (if documents have keyphrases assigned, a user could search by keyphrase to produce more reliable hits than a full-text search), and be employed in generating index entries for a large text corpus.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Depending on the different literature and the definition of key terms, words or phrases, keyword extraction is a highly related theme.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Beginning with the work of Turney, many researchers have approached keyphrase extraction as a supervised machine learning problem.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Given a document, we construct an example for each unigram, bigram, and trigram found in the text (though other text units are also possible, as discussed below).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] We then compute various features describing each example (e.g., does the phrase begin with an upper-case letter?).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] We assume there are known keyphrases available for a set of training documents.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Using the known keyphrases, we can assign positive or negative labels to the examples.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Then we learn a classifier that can discriminate between positive and negative examples as a function of the features.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Some classifiers make a binary classification for a test example, while others assign a probability of being a keyphrase.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For instance, in the above text, we might learn a rule that says phrases with initial capital letters are likely to be keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] After training a learner, we can select keyphrases for test documents in the following manner.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] We apply the same example-generation strategy to the test documents, then run each example through the learner.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] We can determine the keyphrases by looking at binary classification decisions or probabilities returned from our learned model.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] If probabilities are given, a threshold is used to select the keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Keyphrase extractors are generally evaluated using precision and recall.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Precision measures how many of the proposed keyphrases are actually correct.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Recall measures how many of the true keyphrases your system proposed.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The two measures can be combined in an F-score, which is the harmonic mean of the two (*F* = 2*PR*/(*P* + *R*) ).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Matches between the proposed keyphrases and the known keyphrases can be checked after stemming or applying some other text normalization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Designing a supervised keyphrase extraction system involves deciding on several choices (some of these apply to unsupervised, too).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The first choice is exactly how to generate examples.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Turney and others have used all possible unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams without intervening punctuation and after removing stopwords.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Hulth showed that you can get some improvement by selecting examples to be sequences of tokens that match certain patterns of part-of-speech tags.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Ideally, the mechanism for generating examples produces all the known labeled keyphrases as candidates, though this is often not the case.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, if we use only unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams, then we will never be able to extract a known keyphrase containing four words.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] However, generating too many examples can also lead to low precision.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] We also need to create features that describe the examples and are informative enough to allow a learning algorithm to discriminate keyphrases from non- keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Typically features involve various term frequencies (how many times a phrase appears in the current text or in a larger corpus), the length of the example, relative position of the first occurrence, various Boolean syntactic features (e.g., contains all caps), etc.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The Turney paper used about 12 such features.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Hulth uses a reduced set of features, which were found most successful in the KEA (Keyphrase Extraction Algorithm) work derived from Turney's seminal paper.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In the end, the system will need to return a list of keyphrases for a test document, so we need to have a way to limit the number.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Ensemble methods (i.e., using votes from several classifiers) have been used to produce numeric scores that can be thresholded to provide a user-provided number of keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This is the technique used by Turney with C4.5 decision trees.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Hulth used a single binary classifier so the learning algorithm implicitly determines the appropriate number.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Once examples and features are created, we need a way to learn to predict keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Virtually any supervised learning algorithm could be used, such as decision trees, Naive Bayes, and rule induction.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In the case of Turney's GenEx algorithm, a genetic algorithm is used to learn parameters for a domain-specific keyphrase extraction algorithm.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The extractor follows a series of heuristics to identify keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The genetic algorithm optimizes parameters for these heuristics with respect to performance on training documents with known key phrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Another keyphrase extraction algorithm is TextRank.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] While supervised methods have some nice properties, like being able to produce interpretable rules for what features characterize a keyphrase, they also require a large amount of training data.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Many documents with known keyphrases are needed.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Furthermore, training on a specific domain tends to customize the extraction process to that domain, so the resulting classifier is not necessarily portable, as some of Turney's results demonstrate.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Unsupervised keyphrase extraction removes the need for training data.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It approaches the problem from a different angle.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Instead of trying to learn explicit features that characterize keyphrases, the TextRank algorithm exploits the structure of the text itself to determine keyphrases that appear "central" to the text in the same way that PageRank selects important Web pages.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Recall this is based on the notion of "prestige" or "recommendation" from social networks.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In this way, TextRank does not rely on any previous training data at all, but rather can be run on any arbitrary piece of text, and it can produce output simply based on the text's intrinsic properties.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus the algorithm is easily portable to new domains and languages.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] TextRank is a general purpose graph-based ranking algorithm for NLP.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Essentially, it runs PageRank on a graph specially designed for a particular NLP task.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For keyphrase extraction, it builds a graph using some set of text units as vertices.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Edges are based on some measure of semantic or lexical similarity between the text unit vertices.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Unlike PageRank, the edges are typically undirected and can be weighted to reflect a degree of similarity.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The vertices should correspond to what we want to rank.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Potentially, we could do something similar to the supervised methods and create a vertex for each unigram, bigram, trigram, etc.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] However, to keep the graph small, the authors decide to rank individual unigrams in a first step, and then include a second step that merges highly ranked adjacent unigrams to form multi-word phrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This has a nice side effect of allowing us to produce keyphrases of arbitrary length.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, if we rank unigrams and find that "advanced", "natural", "language", and "processing" all get high ranks, then we would look at the original text and see that these words appear consecutively and create a final keyphrase using all four together.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Note that the unigrams placed in the graph can be filtered by part of speech.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The authors found that adjectives and nouns were the best to include.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus, some linguistic knowledge comes into play in this step.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Edges are created based on word co-occurrence in this application of TextRank.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Two vertices are connected by an edge if the unigrams appear within a window of size N in the original text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus, "natural" and "language" might be linked in a text about NLP.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] "Natural" and "processing" would also be linked because they would both appear in the same string of N words.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] These edges build on the notion of "text cohesion" and the idea that words that appear near each other are likely related in a meaningful way and "recommend" each other to the reader.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Since this method simply ranks the individual vertices, we need a way to threshold or produce a limited number of keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The technique chosen is to set a count T to be a user-specified fraction of the total number of vertices in the graph.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Then the top T vertices/unigrams are selected based on their stationary probabilities.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A post- processing step is then applied to merge adjacent instances of these T unigrams.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] As a result, potentially more or less than T final keyphrases will be produced, but the number should be roughly proportional to the length of the original text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It is not initially clear why applying PageRank to a co-occurrence graph would produce useful keyphrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] One way to think about it is the following.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A word that appears multiple times throughout a text may have many different co-occurring neighbors.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, in a text about machine learning, the unigram "learning" might co-occur with "machine", "supervised", "un-supervised", and "semi-supervised" in four different sentences.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus, the "learning" vertex would be a central "hub" that connects to these other modifying words.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Running PageRank/TextRank on the graph is likely to rank "learning" highly.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, if the text contains the phrase "supervised classification", then there would be an edge between "supervised" and "classification".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] If "classification" appears several other places and thus has many neighbors, its importance would contribute to the importance of "supervised".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] If it ends up with a high rank, it will be selected as one of the top T unigrams, along with "learning" and probably "classification".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In the final post-processing step, we would then end up with keyphrases "supervised learning" and "supervised classification".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In short, the co-occurrence graph will contain densely connected regions for terms that appear often and in different contexts.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A random walk on this graph will have a stationary distribution that assigns large probabilities to the terms in the centers of the clusters.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This is similar to densely connected Web pages getting ranked highly by PageRank.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This approach has also been used in document summarization, considered below.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Like keyphrase extraction, document summarization aims to identify the essence of a text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The only real difference is that now we are dealing with larger text units—whole sentences instead of words and phrases.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Supervised text summarization is very much like supervised keyphrase extraction.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Basically, if you have a collection of documents and human-generated summaries for them, you can learn features of sentences that make them good candidates for inclusion in the summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Features might include the position in the document (i.e., the first few sentences are probably important), the number of words in the sentence, etc.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The main difficulty in supervised extractive summarization is that the known summaries must be manually created by extracting sentences so the sentences in an original training document can be labeled as "in summary" or "not in summary".
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This is not typically how people create summaries, so simply using journal abstracts or existing summaries is usually not sufficient.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The sentences in these summaries do not necessarily match up with sentences in the original text, so it would be difficult to assign labels to examples for training.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Note, however, that these natural summaries can still be used for evaluation purposes, since ROUGE-1 evaluation only considers unigrams.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] During the DUC 2001 and 2002 evaluation workshops, TNO developed a sentence extraction system for multi-document summarization in the news domain.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The system was based on a hybrid system using a Naive Bayes classifier and statistical language models for modeling salience.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Although the system exhibited good results, the researchers wanted to explore the effectiveness of a maximum entropy (ME) classifier for the meeting summarization task, as ME is known to be robust against feature dependencies.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Maximum entropy has also been applied successfully for summarization in the broadcast news domain.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A promising approach is adaptive document/text summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It involves first recognizing the text genre and then applying summarization algorithms optimized for this genre.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The unsupervised approach to summarization is also quite similar in spirit to unsupervised keyphrase extraction and gets around the issue of costly training data.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Some unsupervised summarization approaches are based on finding a "centroid" sentence, which is the mean word vector of all the sentences in the document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Then the sentences can be ranked with regard to their similarity to this centroid sentence.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A more principled way to estimate sentence importance is using random walks and eigenvector centrality.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] LexRank is an algorithm essentially identical to TextRank, and both use this approach for document summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The two methods were developed by different groups at the same time, and LexRank simply focused on summarization, but could just as easily be used for keyphrase extraction or any other NLP ranking task.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In both LexRank and TextRank, a graph is constructed by creating a vertex for each sentence in the document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The edges between sentences are based on some form of semantic similarity or content overlap.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] While LexRank uses cosine similarity of TF-IDF vectors, TextRank uses a very similar measure based on the number of words two sentences have in common (normalized by the sentences' lengths).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The LexRank paper explored using unweighted edges after applying a threshold to the cosine values, but also experimented with using edges with weights equal to the similarity score.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] TextRank uses continuous similarity scores as weights.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In both algorithms, the sentences are ranked by applying PageRank to the resulting graph.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A summary is formed by combining the top ranking sentences, using a threshold or length cutoff to limit the size of the summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In this case, some training documents might be needed, though the TextRank results show the additional features are not absolutely necessary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Unlike TextRank, LexRank has been applied to multi-document summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Multi-document summarization creates information reports that are both concise and comprehensive.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] With different opinions being put together and outlined, every topic is described from multiple perspectives within a single document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Automatic summaries present information extracted from multiple sources algorithmically, without any editorial touch or subjective human intervention, thus making it completely unbiased.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Multi-document extractive summarization faces a problem of redundancy.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Ideally, we want to extract sentences that are both "central" (i.e., contain the main ideas) and "diverse" (i.e., they differ from one another).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, in a set of news articles about some event, each article is likely to have many similar sentences.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] To address this issue, LexRank applies a heuristic post-processing step that adds sentences in rank order, but discards sentences that are too similar to ones already in the summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This method is called Cross-Sentence Information Subsumption (CSIS).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] These methods work based on the idea that sentences "recommend" other similar sentences to the reader.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus, if one sentence is very similar to many others, it will likely be a sentence of great importance.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Its importance also stems from the importance of the sentences "recommending" it.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Thus, to get ranked highly and placed in a summary, a sentence must be similar to many sentences that are in turn also similar to many other sentences.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This makes intuitive sense and allows the algorithms to be applied to an arbitrary new text.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The methods are domain-independent and easily portable.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] One could imagine the features indicating important sentences in the news domain might vary considerably from the biomedical domain.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] However, the unsupervised "recommendation"-based approach applies to any domain.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In addition to explicitly promoting diversity during the ranking process, GRASSHOPPER incorporates a prior ranking (based on sentence position in the case of summarization).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The state of the art results for multi-document summarization are obtained using mixtures of submodular functions.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] These methods have achieved the state of the art results for Document Summarization Corpora, DUC 04 - 07.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similar results were achieved with the use of determinantal point processes (which are a special case of submodular functions) for DUC-04.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A new method for multi-lingual multi-document summarization that avoids redundancy generates ideograms to represent the meaning of each sentence in each document, then evaluates similarity by comparing ideogram shape and position.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It does not use word frequency, training or preprocessing.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It uses two user-supplied parameters: equivalence (when are two sentences to be considered equivalent?) and relevance (how long is the desired summary?).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The idea of a submodular set function has recently emerged as a powerful modeling tool for various summarization problems.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Submodular functions naturally model notions of *coverage*, *information*, *representation* and *diversity*.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Moreover, several important combinatorial optimization problems occur as special instances of submodular optimization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, the set cover problem is a special case of submodular optimization, since the set cover function is submodular.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The set cover function attempts to find a subset of objects which *cover* a given set of concepts.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, in document summarization, one would like the summary to cover all important and relevant concepts in the document.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, the facility location problem is a special case of submodular functions.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The Facility Location function also naturally models coverage and diversity.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Another example of a submodular optimization problem is using a determinantal point process to model diversity.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, the Maximum-Marginal-Relevance procedure can also be seen as an instance of submodular optimization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] All these important models encouraging coverage, diversity and information are all submodular.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Moreover, submodular functions can be efficiently combined, and the resulting function is still submodular.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Hence, one could combine one submodular function which models diversity, another one which models coverage and use human supervision to learn a right model of a submodular function for the problem.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] While submodular functions are fitting problems for summarization, they also admit very efficient algorithms for optimization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, a simple greedy algorithm admits a constant factor guarantee.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Moreover, the greedy algorithm is extremely simple to implement and can scale to large datasets, which is very important for summarization problems.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Submodular functions have achieved state-of-the-art for almost all summarization problems.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, work by Lin and Bilmes, 2012 shows that submodular functions achieve the best results to date on DUC-04, DUC-05, DUC-06 and DUC-07 systems for document summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, work by Lin and Bilmes, 2011, shows that many existing systems for automatic summarization are instances of submodular functions.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This was a breakthrough result establishing submodular functions as the right models for summarization problems.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Submodular Functions have also been used for other summarization tasks.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Tschiatschek et al., 2014 show that mixtures of submodular functions achieve state-of-the-art results for image collection summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, Bairi et al., 2015 show the utility of submodular functions for summarizing multi-document topic hierarchies.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Submodular Functions have also successfully been used for summarizing machine learning datasets.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The most common way to evaluate the informativeness of automatic summaries is to compare them with human-made model summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Evaluation can be intrinsic or extrinsic, and inter-textual or intra-textual.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Intrinsic evaluation assesses the summaries directly, while extrinsic evaluation evaluates how the summarization system affects the completion of some other task.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Intrinsic evaluations have assessed mainly the coherence and informativeness of summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Extrinsic evaluations, on the other hand, have tested the impact of summarization on tasks like relevance assessment, reading comprehension, etc.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Intra-textual evaluation assess the output of a specific summarization system, while inter-textual evaluation focuses on contrastive analysis of outputs of several summarization systems.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Human judgement often varies greatly in what it considers a "good" summary, so creating an automatic evaluation process is particularly difficult.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Manual evaluation can be used, but this is both time and labor-intensive, as it requires humans to read not only the summaries but also the source documents.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Other issues are those concerning coherence and coverage.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The most common way to evaluate summaries is ROUGE (Recall-Oriented Understudy for Gisting Evaluation).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It is very common for summarization and translation systems in NIST's Document Understanding Conferences.[2] ROUGE is a recall-based measure of how well a summary covers the content of human-generated summaries known as references.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It calculates n-gram overlaps between automatically generated summaries and previously written human summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] It is recall-based to encourage inclusion of all important topics in summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Recall can be computed with respect to unigram, bigram, trigram, or 4-gram matching.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] For example, ROUGE-1 is the fraction of unigrams that appear in both the reference summary and the automatic summary out of all unigrams in the reference summary.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] If there are multiple reference summaries, their scores are averaged.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] A high level of overlap should indicate a high degree of shared concepts between the two summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] ROUGE cannot determine if the result is coherent, that is if sentences flow together in a sensibly.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] High-order n-gram ROUGE measures help to some degree.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Another unsolved problem is Anaphor resolution.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Similarly, for image summarization, Tschiatschek et al., developed a Visual-ROUGE score which judges the performance of algorithms for image summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Domain-independent summarization techniques apply sets of general features to identify information-rich text segments.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Recent research focuses on domain-specific summarization using knowledge specific to the text's domain, such as medical knowledge and ontologies for summarizing medical texts.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The main drawback of the evaluation systems so far is that we need a reference summary (for some methods, more than one), to compare automatic summaries with models.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Much effort has to be made to create corpora of texts and their corresponding summaries.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Furthermore, some methods require manual annotation of the summaries (e.g.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Moreover, they all perform a quantitative evaluation with regard to different similarity metrics.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] The first publication in the area dates back to 1957 (Hans Peter Luhn), starting with a statistical technique.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Research increased significantly in 2015.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Term frequency–inverse document frequency had been used by 2016.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Pattern-based summarization was the most powerful option for multi-document summarization found by 2016.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] In the following year it was surpassed by latent semantic analysis (LSA) combined with non-negative matrix factorization (NMF).
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Although they did not replace other approaches and are often combined with them, by 2019 machine learning methods dominated the extractive summarization of single documents, which was considered to be nearing maturity.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] By 2020, the field was still very active and research is shifting towards abstractive summation and real-time summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] Recently the rise of transformer models replacing more traditional RNN (LSTM) have provided a flexibility in the mapping of text sequences to text sequences of a different type, which is well suited to automatic summarization.
[src:text-summarization/automatic-summarization] This includes models such as T5 and Pegasus.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:text-summarization/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Given an image representing printed text, determine the corresponding text.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Given a sound clip of a person or people speaking, determine the textual representation of the speech.
