[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Introduction and creation of language metamodels and ontologies are efficient but empirical solutions.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] , or subjective Yes/No vs. objective True/False is expected for the construction of a basis of semantics formalization.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Convert information from computer databases or semantic intents into readable human language.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Not an NLP task proper but an extension of natural language generation and other NLP tasks is the creation of full-fledged books.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] , marketed as a novel, contains sixty million words.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] , this is grounded on factual knowledge and based on text summarization.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:text-summarization/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] seq2seq is an approach to machine translation (or more generally, sequence transduction) with roots in information theory, where communication is understood as an encode-transmit-decode process, and machine translation can be studied as a special case of communication.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] This viewpoint was elaborated, for example, in the noisy channel model of machine translation.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In practice, seq2seq maps an input sequence into a real-numerical vector by using a neural network (the *encoder*), and then maps it back to an output sequence using another neural network (the *decoder*).
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The idea of encoder-decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The papers most commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two papers from 2014.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In the seq2seq as proposed by them, both the encoder and the decoder were LSTMs.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] This had the "bottleneck" problem, since the encoding vector has a fixed size, so for long input sequences, information would tend to be lost, as they are difficult to fit into the fixed-length encoding vector.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The attention mechanism, proposed in 2014, resolved the bottleneck problem.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] They called their model *RNNsearch*, as it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] A problem with seq2seq models at this point was that recurrent neural networks are difficult to parallelize.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The 2017 publication of Transformers resolved the problem by replacing the encoding RNN with self-attention Transformer blocks ("encoder blocks"), and the decoding RNN with cross-attention causally-masked Transformer blocks ("decoder blocks").
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] One of the papers cited as the originator for seq2seq is (Sutskever et al 2014), published at Google Brain while they were on Google's machine translation project.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The research allowed Google to overhaul Google Translate into Google Neural Machine Translation in 2016.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Mikolov had worked on RNNLM (using RNN for language modelling) for his PhD thesis, and is more notable for developing word2vec.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The encoder is responsible for processing the input sequence and capturing its essential information, which is stored as the hidden state of the network and, in a model with attention mechanism, a context vector.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The context vector is the weighted sum of the input hidden states and is generated for every time instance in the output sequences.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The decoder takes the context vector and hidden states from the encoder and generates the final output sequence.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The decoder operates in an autoregressive manner, producing one element of the output sequence at a time.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] At each step, it considers the previously generated elements, the context vector, and the input sequence information to make predictions for the next element in the output sequence.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Specifically, in a model with attention mechanism, the context vector and the hidden state are concatenated together to form an attention hidden vector, which is used as an input for the decoder.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The seq2seq method developed in the early 2010s uses two neural networks: an encoder network converts an input sentence into numerical vectors, and a decoder network converts those vectors to sentences in the target language.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The Attention mechanism was grafted onto this structure in 2014 and is shown below.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Later it was refined into the encoder-decoder Transformer architecture of 2017.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] There is a subtle difference between training and prediction.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] During training time, both the input and the output sequences are known.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] During prediction time, only the input sequence is known, and the output sequence must be decoded by the network itself.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Specifically, consider an input sequence $x_{1:n}$ and output sequence $y_{1:m}$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The encoder would process the input $x_{1:n}$ step by step.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] After that, the decoder would take the output from the encoder, as well as the <bos> as input, and produce a prediction ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Now, the question is: what should be input to the decoder in the next step?
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] A standard method for training is "teacher forcing".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In teacher forcing, no matter what is output by the decoder, the next input to the decoder is always the reference.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] That is, even if ${\hat {y}}_{1}\neq y_{1}$ , the next input to the decoder is still $y_{1}$ , and so on.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] During prediction time, the "teacher" $y_{1:m}$ would be unavailable.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Therefore, the input to the decoder must be ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ , then ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ , and so on.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] It is found that if a model is trained purely by teacher forcing, its performance would degrade during prediction time, since generation based on the model's own output is different from generation based on the teacher's output.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] This is called exposure bias or a train/test distribution shift.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] A 2015 paper recommends that, during training, randomly switch between teacher forcing and no teacher forcing.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The attention mechanism is an enhancement introduced by Bahdanau et al. in 2014 to address limitations in the basic Seq2Seq architecture where a longer input sequence results in the hidden state output of the encoder becoming irrelevant for the decoder.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] It enables the model to selectively focus on different parts of the input sequence during the decoding process.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] At each decoder step, an alignment model calculates the attention score using the current decoder state and all of the attention hidden vectors as input.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] An alignment model is another neural network model that is trained jointly with the seq2seq model used to calculate how well an input, represented by the hidden state, matches with the previous output, represented by attention hidden state.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] A softmax function is then applied to the attention score to get the attention weight.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In some models, the encoder states are directly fed into an activation function, removing the need for alignment model.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] An activation function receives one decoder state and one encoder state and returns a scalar value of their relevance.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Consider the seq2seq language English-to-French translation task.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] To be concrete, let us consider the translation of "the zone of international control <end>", which should translate to "la zone de contrôle international <end>".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <end> token as a control character to delimit the end of input for both the encoder and the decoder.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] An input sequence of text $x_{0},x_{1},\dots$ is processed by a neural network (which can be an LSTM, a Transformer encoder, or some other network) into a sequence of real-valued vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ , where h stands for "hidden vector".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] After the encoder has finished processing, the decoder starts operating over the hidden vectors, to produce an output sequence $y_{0},y_{1},\dots$ , autoregressively.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <start> token as a control character to delimit the start of input for the decoder.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The decoding terminates as soon as "<end>" appears in the decoder output.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] As hand-crafting weights defeats the purpose of machine learning, the model must compute the attention weights on its own.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Taking analogy from the language of database queries, we make the model construct a triple of vectors: key, query, and value.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The rough idea is that we have a "database" in the form of a list of key-value pairs.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The decoder sends in a **query**, and obtains a reply in the form of a weighted sum of the **values**, where the weight is proportional to how closely the query resembles each **key**.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The decoder first processes the "<start>" input partially, to obtain an intermediate vector $h_{0}^{d}$ , the 0th hidden vector of decoder.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Then, the intermediate vector is transformed by a linear map $W^{Q}$ into a **query** vector $q_{0}=h_{0}^{d}W^{Q}$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Meanwhile, the hidden vectors outputted by the encoder are transformed by another linear map $W^{K}$ into **key** vectors $k_{0}=h_{0}W^{K},k_{1}=h_{1}W^{K},\dots$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The linear maps are useful for providing the model with enough freedom to find the best way to represent the data.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Ideally, the model should have learned to compute the keys and values, such that $q_{0}k_{0}^{T}$ is large, $q_{0}k_{1}^{T}$ is small, and the rest are very small.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] This can be interpreted as saying that the attention weight should be mostly applied to the 0th hidden vector of the encoder, a little to the 1st, and essentially none to the rest.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In order to make a properly weighted sum, we need to transform this list of dot products into a probability distribution over $0,1,\dots$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] where $v_{0}=h_{0}W^{V},v_{1}=h_{1}W^{V},\dots$ are the **value** vectors, linearly transformed by another matrix to provide the model with freedom to find the best way to represent values.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Without the matrices $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ , the model would be forced to use the same hidden vector for both key and value, which might not be appropriate, as these two tasks are not the same.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The particular version described in this section is "decoder cross-attention", as the output context vector is used by the decoder, and the input keys and values come from the encoder, but the query comes from the decoder, thus "cross-attention".
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Note that the querying vector, $h_{0}^{d}$ , is not necessarily the same as the key-value vector $h_{0}$ .
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In fact, it is theoretically possible for query, key, and value vectors to all be different, though that is rarely done in practice.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In 2019, Facebook announced its use in symbolic integration and resolution of differential equations.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The company claimed that it could solve complex equations more rapidly and with greater accuracy than commercial solutions such as Mathematica, MATLAB and Maple.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] First, the equation is parsed into a tree structure to avoid notational idiosyncrasies.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] An LSTM neural network then applies its standard pattern recognition facilities to process the tree.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In 2020, Google released Meena, a 2.6 billion parameter seq2seq-based chatbot trained on a 341 GB data set.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Google claimed that the chatbot has 1.7 times greater model capacity than OpenAI's GPT-2.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] In 2022, Amazon introduced AlexaTM 20B, a moderate-sized (20 billion parameter) seq2seq language model.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] It uses an encoder-decoder to accomplish few-shot learning.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The encoder outputs a representation of the input that the decoder uses as input to perform a specific task, such as translating the input into another language.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] The model outperforms the much larger GPT-3 in language translation and summarization.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] Training mixes denoising (appropriately inserting missing text in strings) and causal-language-modeling (meaningfully extending an input text).
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] It allows adding features across different languages without massive training workflows.
[src:text-summarization/seq2seq] AlexaTM 20B achieved state-of-the-art performance in few-shot-learning tasks across all Flores-101 language pairs, outperforming GPT-3 on several tasks.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Compare speech segmentation, the process of dividing speech into linguistically meaningful portions.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Word segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component words.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In English and many other languages using some form of the Latin alphabet, the space is a good approximation of a word divider (word delimiter), although this concept has limits because of the variability with which languages emically regard collocations and compounds.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In contrast, German compound nouns show less orthographic variation, with solidification being a stronger norm.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] However, the equivalent to the word space character is not found in all written scripts, and without it word segmentation is a difficult problem.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Languages which do not have a trivial word segmentation process include Chinese, Japanese, where sentences but not words are delimited, Thai and Lao, where phrases and sentences but not words are delimited, and Vietnamese, where syllables but not words are delimited.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In some writing systems however, such as the Ge'ez script used for Amharic and Tigrinya among other languages, words are explicitly delimited (at least historically) with a non-whitespace character.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] The Unicode Consortium has published a *Standard Annex on Text Segmentation*, exploring the issues of segmentation in multiscript texts.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Word splitting may also refer to the process of hyphenation.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Some scholars have suggested that modern Chinese should be written in word segmentation, with spaces between words like written English.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Because there are ambiguous texts where only the author knows the intended meaning.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] For example, "美国会不同意。" may mean "美国 会 不同意。" (The US will not agree.) or "美 国会 不同意。" (The US Congress does not agree).
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] For more details, see Chinese word-segmented writing.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Intent segmentation is the problem of dividing written words into keyphrases (2 or more group of words).
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In English and all other languages the core intent or desire is identified and become the corner-stone of the keyphrase Intent segmentation.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Core product/service, idea, action & or thought anchor the keyphrase.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Sentence segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component sentences.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In English and some other languages, using punctuation, particularly the full stop/period character is a reasonable approximation.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] However even in English this problem is not trivial due to the use of the full stop character for abbreviations, which may or may not also terminate a sentence.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] For example, *Mr.* is not its own sentence in "*Mr.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Smith went to the shops in Jones Street."* When processing plain text, tables of abbreviations that contain periods can help prevent incorrect assignment of sentence boundaries.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] As with word segmentation, not all written languages contain punctuation characters that are useful for approximating sentence boundaries.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Topic analysis consists of two main tasks: topic identification and text segmentation.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] While the first is a simple classification of a specific text, the latter case implies that a document may contain multiple topics, and the task of computerized text segmentation may be to discover these topics automatically and segment the text accordingly.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] The topic boundaries may be apparent from section titles and paragraphs.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] In other cases, one needs to use techniques similar to those used in document classification.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] It is also needed in topic detection and tracking systems and text summarizing problems.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Many different approaches have been tried: e.g.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] HMM, lexical chains, passage similarity using word co-occurrence, clustering, topic modeling, etc.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] It is quite an ambiguous task – people evaluating the text segmentation systems often differ in topic boundaries.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Hence, text segment evaluation is also a challenging problem.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Processes may be required to segment text into segments besides mentioned, including morphemes (a task usually called morphological analysis) or paragraphs.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Automatic segmentation is the problem in natural language processing of implementing a computer process to segment text.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] When punctuation and similar clues are not consistently available, the segmentation task often requires fairly non-trivial techniques, such as statistical decision-making, large dictionaries, as well as consideration of syntactic and semantic constraints.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Effective natural language processing systems and text segmentation tools usually operate on text in specific domains and sources.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] As an example, processing text used in medical records is a very different problem than processing news articles or real estate advertisements.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] The process of developing text segmentation tools starts with collecting a large corpus of text in an application domain.
[src:text-summarization/text-segmentation] Some text segmentation systems take advantage of any markup like HTML and know document formats like PDF to provide additional evidence for sentence and paragraph boundaries.
